<subSubSection pageId="0" pageNumber="62878" type="notes">
<paragraph pageId="0" pageNumber="62878">Notes</paragraph>
<paragraph pageId="0" pageNumber="62878">
This weed of uncertain origin (possibly North America) doubtlessly has been overlooked. It was recently reported from several localities in La Palma, for the first time in the Canary Islands, where it is considered to be naturalised and in expansion (
<bibRefCitation author="Otto, R" journalOrPublisher="Collectanea Botanica" pageId="0" pageNumber="62878" refId="B6509388" refString="Otto, R, Verloove, F, 2016. New xenophytes from La Palma (Canary Islands, Spain), with emphasis on naturalized and (potentially) invasive species. Collectanea Botanica 35" title="New xenophytes from La Palma (Canary Islands, Spain), with emphasis on naturalized and (potentially) invasive species" volume="35" year="2016">Otto and Verloove 2016</bibRefCitation>
). It differs from 
<taxonomicName authority="" authorityName="" class="Centricae" family="Chironomidae" genus="C." higherTaxonomySource="GBIF" kingdom="Animalia" lsidName="C. album" order="Diptera" pageId="0" pageNumber="62878" phylum="Diatomeae" rank="species" species="album">
<emphasis italics="true" pageId="0" pageNumber="62878">C. album</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
by leaves that are large and leathery and with a distinct purple or orange pigmentation.
</paragraph>
<paragraph pageId="0" pageNumber="62878">It is here reported for the first time from Tenerife. In and near some dried out ponds in Erjos, it was seen in abundance in 2016. It probably also occurs elsewhere.</paragraph>
</subSubSection>
